To solve this, we first express both sides of the equation with the same base.
\begin{align*}27^8&=(3\cdot 9)^8\\&=3^8\cdot 9^8\end{align*}
Now,
\begin{align*}27^8&=9^q\\3^8\cdot 9^8 &= 9^q\\3^8&=9^{q-8}\\3^8&=(3^2)^{q-8}\\3^8&=3^{2(q-8)}\end{align*}
So we get the equation $3^{2(q-8)}=3^8$, so that $2(q-8)=8$, which means $q=12$. QED.</think> <answer>12</answer>

problem:
Given that $BDEF$ is a square and $AB = BC = 1$, find the number of square units in the area of the regular octagon.

[asy]
real x = sqrt(2);
pair A,B,C,D,E,F,G,H;
F=(0,0); E=(2,0); D=(2+x,x); C=(2+x,2+x);
B=(2,2+2x); A=(0,2+2x); H=(-x,2+x); G=(-x,x);
draw(A--B--C--D--E--F--G--H--cycle);
draw((-x,0)--(2+x,0)--(2+x,2+2x)--(-x,2+2x)--cycle);
label("$B$",(-x,2+2x),NW); label("$D$",(2+x,2+2x),NE); label("$E$",(2+x,0),SE); label("$F$",(-x,0),SW);
label("$A$",(-x,x+2),W); label("$C$",(0,2+2x),N);
[/asy]

