Now,
\[\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{5n-1}{k^n} = \frac{5}{k}\left(\frac{1}{k}+\frac{2}{k^2}+\frac{3}{k^3}+\cdots\right)-\frac{1}{k}\left(\frac{1}{k}+\frac{1}{k^2}+\frac{1}{k^3}+\cdots\right).\]

Interchanging the sums on the right-hand side,

\[\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{5n-1}{k^n} = \frac{5}{k}\left(\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{n}{k^n}\right)-\frac{1}{k}\left(\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{k^n}\right).\]

This is the same as

\[\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{5n-1}{k^n} = \frac{5}{k}S_1-\frac{1}{k}S,\]

where $S$ and $S_1$ are respectively the sums of the geometric and arith-metric series:

\begin{align*}
S &= \frac{1}{k}+\frac{1}{k^2}+\frac{1}{k^3}+\cdots = \frac{\frac{1}{k}}{1-\frac{1}{k}} = \frac{1}{k-1}
\end{align*}

and

\begin{align*}
S_1 &= \frac{1}{k}+\frac{2}{k^2}+\frac{3}{k^3}+\cdots
= \frac{\frac{1}{k}}{1-\frac{1}{k}}+ \frac{\frac{1}{k^2}}{\left(1-\frac{1}{k}\right)^2}
= \frac{k}{k-1}+\frac{1}{(k-1)^2}.
\end{align*}

Therefore

\[\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} \frac{5n-1}{k^n} = \frac{5\cdot k^2-5k+1}{k(k-1)^3}.\]

Taking reciprocals, we find that $k=\boxed{\frac{9}{2}}$.</answer>

